

In the spiral the numbers are placed on the integer lattice as  

\[
\begin{array}{ccc}
\cdots &5&4&3&\cdots\\
\cdots &6&1&2&\cdots\\
\cdots &7&8&9&\cdots
\end{array}
\]

so that the centre \((0,0)\) holds \(1\), the number \(2\) is at \((1,0)\), then the spiral proceeds right, up, left, down, …

---

### 1.  Position of 2026  

For a given integer \(n\), let  

\[
k=\Big\lceil\frac{\sqrt{n}-1}{2}\Big\rceil .
\]

The number \(n\) lies on the square of side \(2k+1\) (the “\(k\)-th layer”).  

Because  

\[
45^{2}=2025<2026<47^{2}=2209,
\]

the smallest odd square \(\ge\sqrt{2026}\) is \(47^{2}\); hence \(k=23\) and the side‑length of the layer is \(2k+1=47\).

The first number of a layer is at \((k,-k+1)\).  
Thus  

\[
2026\quad\longrightarrow\quad (x,y)=(23,-22).
\]

---

### 2.  The eight neighbour coordinates  

\[
\begin{aligned}
\text{W:}&\;(22,-22),\\
\text{E:}&\;(24,-22),\\
\text{N:}&\;(23,-21),\\
\text{S:}&\;(23,-23),\\
\text{NW:}&\;(22,-21),\\
\text{NE:}&\;(24,-21),\\
\text{SW:}&\;(22,-23),\\
\text{SE:}&\;(24,-23).
\end{aligned}
\]

---

### 3.  Converting a coordinate \((x,y)\) to its number  

For a point \((x,y)\) let  

\[
k=\max(|x|,|y|),\qquad s=2k+1,\qquad M=s^{2}.
\]

If \(k=0\) the number is \(1\).  
Otherwise the offset from the corner \((k,-k)\) (which holds the value \(M\)) is

\[
\text{offset}= 
\begin{cases}
k-x,&\text{if }y=-k,\\[2pt]
2k+(y+k),&\text{if }x=-k,\\[2pt]
4k+(x+k),&\text{if }y=k,\\[2pt]
6k+(k-y),&\text{if }x=k,
\end{cases}
\]

and the number at \((x,y)\) is \(M-\text{offset}\).

Applying this gives  

\[
\begin{array}{c|c}
\text{coordinate} & \text{value}\\\hline
(22,-22) & 2025\\
(24,-22) & 2211\\
(23,-21) & 2027\\
(23,-23) & 2209\\
(22,-21) & 1850\\
(24,-21) & 2212\\
(22,-23) & 2208\\
(24,-23) & 2210
\end{array}
\]

---

### 4.  Summing the eight neighbours  

\[
\begin{aligned}
\sum &=2025+2211+2027+2209\\
    &\qquad+1850+2212+2208+2210\\
    &=16952 .
\end{aligned}
\]

---

\[
\boxed{16952}
\]
